<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910918-0002</DOCNO><DOCID>910918-0002.</DOCID><HL>   TransTechnology   Sets Panel to Decide   Which Units to Keep</HL><DATE>09/18/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B5</SO><CO>   TT WNEWS</CO><MS>TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>AEROSPACE (ARO)</IN><NS>PERSONNEL ANNOUNCEMENTS, PROMOTIONS, APPOINTMENTS (PER)RESTRUCTURINGS, RECAPITALIZATION (RCN)</NS><RE>CALIFORNIA (CA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   LOS ANGELES -- TransTechnology Corp. said it formed acommittee to evaluate which units it will discontinue or sellin a &quot;major restructuring&quot; aimed at enhancing profitability.   The maker of aerospace, advanced-technology and industrialproducts also said Michael J. Berthelot, chief executiveofficer of Canterbury Holdings Corp., an investment companybased in Hudson, Ohio, was named to the newly createdposition of vice chairman. Mr. Berthelot, 41 years old, holdsa 5.3% stake in TransTechnology and was elected a directorthis year.</LP><TEXT>   Mr. Berthelot said he would largely coordinate investorrelations, a job performed until now by Arch Scurlock,TransTechnology's 73-year-old chairman. Dr. Scurlock recentlyhad a heart valve replacement and &quot;has been ill for severalmonths,&quot; Mr. Berthelot said.   Formation of the restructuring committee follows theappointment earlier this year of an investment firm torecommend &quot;long-term and short-term strategies&quot; to enableshareholders to achieve maximum value for their shares. Thatfirm, Mr. Berthelot said, determined that &quot;we're in a numberof businesses, few of which are complimentary, havesynergies, or economies of scale.&quot; It also gave an estimatedvaluation of the company's various units. Mr. Berthelot saidthe company will in the next 45 days determine which units tosell after completing an analysis of their five-yearprospects.   In late New York Stock Exchange trading yesterday,TransTechnology shares were quoted at $6.50, down 37.5 cents.   In the year ended March 31, the company had a loss of $4million, or 79 cents a share, on revenue of $186.4 million.The results included a loss from discontinued operations of$2.3 million.</TEXT></DOC>